                                                                                                               Pact signed to ensure smooth Nepal polls
          J. HEMANTH                           A woman holds a ballot paper as she prepares to vote during a mock election at a makeshift polling station in Kathmandu on Tuesday. (Reuters)                                  
	Kathmandu, April 1: Leaders of the ruling seven-party coalition today signed a 10-point agreement to ensure the smooth conduct of the crucial April 10 Constituent Assembly elections.         
	The coalition leaders, including Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala, UML general secretary Madhav Kumar Nepal and Maoist chief Prachanda, signed the agreement after the election commission warned about escalating violence in several parts of Nepal .         
	Chief election commissioner Bhoj Raj Pokharel told the three leaders yesterday that the polls legitimacy would be questioned if the parties continued to violate the poll code of conduct.         
	The agreement states that the elections would be held peacefully and the parties would not take part in violent activities. It also says that the parties would not interfere in each others campaigning and would abide by the code.         
	It says that a committee comprising respectable citizens of the region should be formed at the district level to oversee the elections. Telephone hotlines should be available to citizens at the district police stations, the agreement said.        
	Carter observer        
	The Carter Centre in Kathmandu announced that former US President Jimmy Carter will arrive in Nepal on April 7 with wife Rosalyn.        
	The centre said that Carter would lead an international group of election observers. It will include former Thai deputy Prime Minister Surakiart Sathirathai.                                                                                                                                                                             
